<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
Despite fruits still being unknown for 
<taxonomicName class="Equisetopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. rosmarinifolia" order="Malpighiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="rosmarinifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">H. rosmarinifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, they most likely are similar to the ones of 
<taxonomicName class="Equisetopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. pannosa" order="Malpighiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="pannosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">H. pannosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with the dorsal wing reduced to a crest, and nuts lacking lateral winglets (i.e., wingless nut). Alternatively, most species of the Parabanisteria group present a developed dorsal wing (
<bibRefCitation author="Almeida, RF" journalOrPublisher="Nordic Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" publicationUrl="http://floradobrasil.jbrj.gov.br/" refId="B2" refString="Almeida, RF, Francener, A, Pessoa, CS, Sebastiani, R, Amorim, AMA, Mamede, MCH, 2021. Malpighiaceae monograph in Flora do Brasil 2020. http://floradobrasil.jbrj.gov.br/" title="Malpighiaceae monograph in Flora do Brasil 2020." url="http://floradobrasil.jbrj.gov.br/" year="2021">Almeida et al. 2021</bibRefCitation>
). Floral and fruit characters are highly conserved in the Parabanisteria group and have been traditionally considered of little taxonomic relevance (
<bibRefCitation author="Niedenzu, F" editor="Engler, A" journalOrPublisher="W. Engelmann, Leipzig" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="290 - 385" refId="B9" refString="Niedenzu, F, 1928. Heteropterys. In: Engler, A, Ed., Das Pflanzenreich, IV, 141, Part 2 (Heft 93). W. Engelmann, Leipzig: 290 - 385" title="Heteropterys." volumeTitle="Das Pflanzenreich, IV, 141, Part 2 (Heft 93)." year="1928">Niedenzu 1928</bibRefCitation>
). Consequently, this 
<normalizedToken originalValue="group’s">group's</normalizedToken>
taxonomy currently heavily relies on vegetative characters related to life form, branch, and leaf morphology, rendering it the most taxonomic convoluted in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Heteropterys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Heteropterys" order="Malpighiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Heteropterys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Niedenzu, F" editor="Engler, A" journalOrPublisher="W. Engelmann, Leipzig" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" pagination="290 - 385" refId="B9" refString="Niedenzu, F, 1928. Heteropterys. In: Engler, A, Ed., Das Pflanzenreich, IV, 141, Part 2 (Heft 93). W. Engelmann, Leipzig: 290 - 385" title="Heteropterys." volumeTitle="Das Pflanzenreich, IV, 141, Part 2 (Heft 93)." year="1928">Niedenzu 1928</bibRefCitation>
; Almeida pers. observ.). Further studies are still necessary to properly explore the relevance of floral and fruit characters in this group and review species boundaries. For the time being, we provide below an identification key for the species of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malpighiaceae" genus="Heteropterys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Heteropterys" order="Malpighiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Heteropterys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Parabanisteria group from the State of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Goiás">
<collectingRegion country="Brazil" name="Goias">Goias</collectingRegion>
</normalizedToken>
, 
<collectingCountry name="Brazil">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
